Q: How often will the district revisit the decision on the model chosen to ensure things remain safe?

A: The district will revisit the learning model in use monthly. The goal would be to slowly return to 100% in-person learning. The district will decide what instructional model is being used in conjunction with the local health department.

More frequently asked questions and answers are available on our website here:
http://arkportcsdny.apptegy.us/o/arkportcsd/page/frequently-asked-questions--110

Q: Is the district planning to invest in plexiglass for reception areas of schools and nurses' supplies or tents for schools?

A: Yes, the district will be investing in polycarbonate dividers for offices, the cafeteria, and one-on-one workspaces in classrooms. The district will also be purchasing outdoor tables and renting tents for outdoor classes.

More frequently asked questions and answers are available on our website here:
http://arkportcsdny.apptegy.us/o/arkportcsd/page/frequently-asked-questions--119

post_text:
Q: What tools will be available to help guide parents through emotional health in helping children adjust to the â€˜new normalâ€™?

A: All PK-12 teachers will be using Schoology so families will have just one system for accessing learning materials, assignments, grades and communications. Schoology will streamline the academic piece so that there is less stress at home surrounding student work. In order to address emotional health, students will be engaging in social emotional learning each week. Our PK-12 school counselor will continue to maintain an online bank of resources which can be accessed by parents or students at any time. Parents/guardians should always feel free to contact their students' teachers or the student services team with questions regarding emotional health.

More frequently asked questions and answers are available on our website here: http://arkportcsdny.apptegy.us/o/arkportcsd/page/frequently-asked-questions--119

Q: How will Arkport schools handle drop-off/pick-up?

A: The most significant change to drop-off/pick-up will be that parents and guardians will not be allowed to enter the building. Student drop-off before school will still occur at the PAC. Parents or guardians will be allowed to stay with their child until they reach the second set of double doors.

More frequently asked questions and answers are available on our website here: http://arkportcsdny.apptegy.us/o/arkportcsd/page/frequently-asked-questions--119

Q: How will the district communicate positive cases of COVID-19 in the event schools are reopened?

A: The district will work with the state and local health departments to communicate the possible COVID-19 exposure. This communication with the school community will align with the communication plan in the schoolâ€™s emergency operations plan. In such a circumstance, it is critical to maintaining the confidentiality of the student or staff member as required by the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) and the Family Education Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA). More frequently asked questions and answers are available on our website here: http://arkportcsdny.apptegy.us/o/arkportcsd/page/frequently-asked-questions--119

On Friday, Aug. 7, Governor Cuomo announced that in-person instruction is permitted in all regions of New York state for the start of the 2020-21 school year based on current COVID-19 infection rates, while also outlining new requirements related to school reopening plans.

These requirements include highlighting plans for remote learning, COVID-19 testing and contact tracing. More information about reopening, and a link to those sections of our reopening plan, can be found here.

post_text:
The end of the school year is upon us! Monday, June 15th & Tuesday, June 16th, we will have the End of the Year Supply Drop-Off and Pick-Up.

Please be advised that families with more than one student, can come at a time that works best for them on Monday, and on Tuesday there will be no scheduled times, pick-up will occur from 8:00 AM-5:30 PM.

If we don't see you in person parents and students, thank you so much for your hard work and support this school year. Have a terrific summer and we look forward to seeing you in the fall!

post_text:
We are seeking applicants for the following teaching position for the 20-21 school year:

Pre K-12 Music Teacher

Responsibilities:
Manage and educate students in a classroom setting
Develop and implement engaging lesson plans
Adhere to established teaching curriculum
Maintain positive relationships with students and parents
Document and share student grades and evaluations
Maintain the health and safety of all students

Qualifications:
Strong classroom management skills
Ability to build rapport with students
Excellent written and verbal communication skills
Strong leadership qualities

Interested candidates should visit our website at www.arkportcsd.org and apply under the Employment tab/Erie 1 BOCES applicant tracking system. Questions can be directed to Meg Khork, HR Manager, by calling 607 295-7471 ext: 1416.

post_text: In the book, All I Really Need to Know I Learned in Kindergarten, by Robert Fulghum there is a list of things that students learn in kindergarten. The list of sixteen items includes things like "Share Everything", "Play Fair", "Warm cookies and milk are good for you", and "Take a nap every afternoon". This morning, we learned a new one, "We all need a blanket sometimes." Last night Arkport got its blanket:-)

post_text:
April 13, 2020 will mark one month since students have attended school. During this time, families have shared multiple photos of their children learning at home, and Arkport faculty and staff have worked hard to stay connected to students while they adapt to new forms of instruction. We enjoy receiving your pictures and look forward to receiving more photos during Phase II at learn_home@arkportcsd.org. Most of all, we look forward to having students, families, faculty and staff back in the school building.
Below you will find a 15-minute video review of Phase I in pictures. Enjoy!
#learn_home@arkportcsd.org #arkportpride

post_text:
Shout-Outs!
#1: I had the pleasure of riding the bus with Arkport bus driver Mrs. Pam Dennis this morning and am happy to report that your children are in good hands! Mrs. Dennis is a very caring and conscientious driver. Her efforts and commitment are appreciated.
#2: Also, I feel obliged to mention what great conditions the roads were in this morning--even after a snowy and windy night! Some of the hills and roads that we traveled could have been a little tricky but they were in great shape! Thank you to the local plow drivers!
Be Safe! Be Responsible! Be Respectful!

It's great to have all kinds of friends on the bus ride to school!

post_text:
Our very own Mr. Chichester, Arkport CSD science teacher, will be competing in the Olympic Trials this Saturday, 2/29, from 12:00-3:00 on NBC!
Science teacher Miss Michalak led Arkport students in an assembly to celebrate Mr. Chichester's accomplishment and to wish him luck on Saturday.
Mr. Chichester shared the following tidbits with students:
1). He started running in 4th grade.
2). He runs 10-12 hours per week and has logged 40,000 miles since graduating college.
3). Mr. Chichester's sister is also running in the Olympic Trials on Saturday!
4). In high school his goal was to run a seven minute mile! He now runs a mile in 4 minutes or under!!
5). Mr. Chichester attributes his success to
Commitment, Passion, Support from Family and Friends, and Persistence.

post_text: Students in Miss Crowell's 1st and 2nd grade PE classes have been working on various juggling related and balance skills for the past 2 weeks. The activities included juggling with scarves, balls and beanbags, using devil sticks, spinning plates, cup stacking and some 2nd graders attempted walking on stilts! The activities allowed students opportunities to do activities that help improve hand-eye coordination, increase ambidexterity (having to use both left and right hand) as well as balance. More importantly students learned how important it is to have a positive attitude and determination when starting a new challenge. Each day we celebrated many successes as students accomplished something new!

Today is National Law Enforcement Appreciation Day!

Arkport Central School would like to recognize its very own School Resource Officer, Mr. Jason Flaitz ðŸ‘®â€â™‚ï¸

Officer Flaitz graduated from Arkport Central School in '92, then from Genesee Community College in '95, and soon after joined law enforcement.

Officer Flaitz chose law enforcement as a profession because he loves helping people. He is retired from the New York State Police after 18 years of service. In his spare time, he enjoys hunting, remodeling houses, and spending time with his family.

When asked what he loves most about working at Arkport, Officer Flaitz states:
"My favorite part of working at Arkport is watching the kids grow and overcome challenges, and of course, seeing them smile ðŸ˜

Thank you Officer Flaitz, for everything you do to keep our faculty, staff and students safe here at ACS!

post_text: Earlier this year the Earth Science class collected black walnuts, mixed the hulls in water and left them to rot. This lovely mixture was then strained and boiled down (the cause of the smell upstairs). We used this homemade stain to stain birdhouses we made.
